WEBVTT

00:31.823 --> 00:33.742
[dog barking]

00:44.127 --> 00:48.089
-[engine starts]
-[classical music plays on radio]

00:53.178 --> 00:55.847
[theme music playing]

02:57.552 --> 02:59.846
[school bell rings]

03:01.306 --> 03:02.307
[chattering]

03:11.065 --> 03:14.360
-I'm gonna grab coffee. You want some?
-I had some on the plane.

03:20.450 --> 03:22.619
Excuse me. May I?

03:23.161 --> 03:25.121
Students are welcome to everything.

03:36.633 --> 03:38.801
-Cold season.
-Sorry, what?

03:39.552 --> 03:42.555
-I was just saying it's cold season.
-Oh.

03:46.267 --> 03:48.269
[sighs]

03:48.353 --> 03:49.395
[woman] Bill.

03:50.855 --> 03:53.733
-How are you? Welcome.
-[Tench] Thank you.

03:53.816 --> 03:55.318
[woman] How's your family?

03:55.401 --> 03:57.779
[Tench] Since when do you care
about any of that?

03:57.862 --> 03:59.989
-[woman] I'm adopting a facade of caring.
-[laughs]

04:00.073 --> 04:01.866
-[woman] You want to dive in?
-[Tench] Yeah.

04:03.076 --> 04:04.369
Here he is.

04:04.452 --> 04:07.330
Dr. Wendy Carr, my partner Holden Ford.

04:07.705 --> 04:08.539
Dr. Carr.

04:08.623 --> 04:11.334
Agent Ford. I've read a lot about you.

04:11.417 --> 04:13.336
-About me?
-Your notes.

04:13.419 --> 04:14.837
Uh, thank you.

04:15.546 --> 04:17.590
Okay, um, let's go to my office.

04:20.843 --> 04:22.178
[Carr]  I'm glad this worked out.

04:22.637 --> 04:24.806
When you sent me your notes
from the Kemper meetings,

04:24.889 --> 04:26.557
I was in a real rut with my new book.

04:26.641 --> 04:29.477
-What's your book about?
-It's about white-collar criminals,

04:29.560 --> 04:31.312
men not so different
to your Edmund Kemper.

04:31.396 --> 04:34.148
How do you think the men you study
are similar to Edmund Kemper?

04:34.232 --> 04:37.151
Well, first of all,
they're all psychopaths.

04:37.235 --> 04:39.362
I study captains of industry:

04:39.445 --> 04:42.615
IBM, MGM, Ford, Exxon, you name it.

04:42.699 --> 04:45.952
And sure, these men all have
wives, kids, dogs, goldfish,

04:46.035 --> 04:48.579
but not because they stopped
being psychopaths,

04:48.663 --> 04:50.915
but because they just had
different leanings.

04:50.999 --> 04:53.543
But you think they have the same
underlying personality traits?

04:53.626 --> 04:55.837
Well, Kemper shows
a total lack of remorse,

04:55.920 --> 04:58.089
a lack of inner emotional structure,

04:58.172 --> 05:00.967
no ability to reflect
on the experience of others.

05:01.050 --> 05:03.469
-You saw this in my notes?
-It would've been clearer

05:03.553 --> 05:06.264
if you'd recorded and transcribed
your interviews verbatim,

05:06.347 --> 05:07.640
but yeah.

05:07.724 --> 05:10.435
Although your project
is obviously in the nascent stages,

05:10.518 --> 05:13.313
it already feels like a clear successor
to  The Mask of Sanity,

05:13.396 --> 05:15.356
which, as you know,
is quite a compliment.

05:15.898 --> 05:17.233
Repeat that?  The Mask of...

05:17.317 --> 05:19.152
[Tench] So you're saying
you don't think this,

05:19.235 --> 05:22.155
us interviewing these killers, is crazy?

05:22.238 --> 05:23.323
[Carr] Just the opposite.

05:23.406 --> 05:26.784
I mean, crazy in the way that anyone
with a truly new idea is crazy.

05:26.868 --> 05:29.412
-But no.
-Wow, okay.

05:29.912 --> 05:31.122
That's a relief.

05:31.205 --> 05:33.458
That hasn't really been the feedback
we've gotten so far.

05:33.541 --> 05:36.002
Actually, this is the only feedback
we've gotten so far.

05:36.085 --> 05:38.212
Well, these men are just sitting here,
locked up.

05:38.296 --> 05:40.423
And we're too afraid of the morality of it

05:40.506 --> 05:42.592
to see the far-reaching value
of their insights.

05:42.675 --> 05:44.677
Far-reaching in law enforcement?

05:44.761 --> 05:48.890
Into behavioral science, early detection,
criminology, you name it.

05:49.015 --> 05:51.476
Oh, yes, yes. This is what
I've been saying the whole time.

05:51.559 --> 05:52.560
Oh, have you?

05:52.643 --> 05:55.063
[Carr] You need to put this
on a more formal footing.

05:55.146 --> 05:56.814
It's gonna take a lot of time and energy

05:56.898 --> 06:00.443
to expand it into a larger project
with a specific questionnaire.

06:00.943 --> 06:02.195
Their family histories,

06:02.278 --> 06:04.489
what their thoughts were
on why they did it,

06:04.572 --> 06:07.658
when they were aroused
during the killings, that sort of thing.

06:07.742 --> 06:10.578
Then contrast, compare, and publish.

06:10.661 --> 06:11.496
Publish?

06:11.579 --> 06:14.165
[Carr] Well, you can't just circulate
your findings within the FBI.

06:14.248 --> 06:16.292
-I mean, maybe even turn it into a book.
-A book?

06:16.376 --> 06:18.878
Whoa.
We appreciate the vote of confidence,

06:18.961 --> 06:21.339
but we weren't allowed
to send you those notes.

06:21.422 --> 06:24.342
-We can't publicize what we're doing.
-[Carr] Why not?

06:24.425 --> 06:26.302
[Tench] Our department head
gave us weekends only

06:26.385 --> 06:27.887
and an office in the basement.

06:27.970 --> 06:30.389
We still have students,
we have Road School full-time.

06:30.473 --> 06:32.350
-We can't just drop everything--
-Road School?

06:32.433 --> 06:35.436
We travel around the country
and teach FBI techniques to cops.

06:35.520 --> 06:37.230
-Oh.
-We're seeing Benjamin Miller

06:37.313 --> 06:38.523
in Bridgewater this afternoon.

06:38.606 --> 06:41.567
Road School is what gives us the freedom
to go out and interview these guys.

06:41.651 --> 06:43.194
We can go bit by bit.

06:43.277 --> 06:45.196
Kemper and Miller
and build out from there.

06:45.279 --> 06:47.031
Make a study in our free time,
like you said.

06:47.115 --> 06:49.158
I didn't realize
that this was so informal.

06:49.242 --> 06:53.329
We could make it formal.
We can do that easily. And then a book.

06:53.412 --> 06:54.872
The successor to  The Mask of--

06:54.956 --> 06:57.416
I guess I just wanted to get
another set of eyes,

06:57.500 --> 07:00.795
see if you thought this was valuable
from an academic standpoint.

07:03.131 --> 07:05.341
Have you shown your Kemper notes
to your department head?

07:06.926 --> 07:07.885
No.

07:07.969 --> 07:10.304
Teaching police departments,
can someone else do that?

07:10.388 --> 07:13.141
-Anyone can, it's really not that hard.
-That is not true,

07:13.224 --> 07:14.559
and it's beside the point.

07:14.642 --> 07:16.686
Shepard doesn't even want us
to talk about this.

07:16.769 --> 07:20.022
You really think he's going to say yes
to a full-time academic study?

07:20.106 --> 07:20.940
Never mind a book?

07:24.026 --> 07:27.071
You think people would be interested
in this outside of law enforcement?

07:28.781 --> 07:30.283
I mean, imagine,

07:30.366 --> 07:34.704
like truly imagine what it takes
to bludgeon someone to death.

07:35.455 --> 07:37.665
The lust for control,

07:37.748 --> 07:39.667
the feeling of arousal,

07:39.750 --> 07:42.920
the decision to rape the severed head
of your victim,

07:43.004 --> 07:45.298
to humiliate her corpse.

07:46.841 --> 07:49.886
How could you possibly get that
from an ordinary police report?

07:50.803 --> 07:53.973
You know why it took me nearly a decade
to publish my book?

07:54.390 --> 07:57.310
Because narcissists
don't go to the doctor.

07:57.810 --> 08:00.438
Psychopaths are convinced
that there is nothing wrong with them.

08:00.521 --> 08:02.982
So these men
are virtually impossible to study.

08:03.065 --> 08:08.112
Yet you have found a way to study them
in near perfect laboratory conditions.

08:08.196 --> 08:11.824
That's what make this so exciting
and potentially so far-reaching.

08:11.908 --> 08:14.535
It's not that I disagree.
I've spent enough time with Holden

08:14.619 --> 08:17.163
that I know what it means
when he gets that crazy look.

08:17.246 --> 08:20.583
I'm afraid it's just not feasible
within the bureaucracy of the FBI.

08:20.666 --> 08:23.753
We've got weekends.
We've got the evenings after Road School,

08:23.836 --> 08:26.797
an hour or so before Road School.
We don't have to tell Shepard.

08:26.881 --> 08:29.592
Interviewing 40 men across the States
is a full-time job.

08:29.675 --> 08:32.053
And if you want this to be
a legitimate academic study,

08:32.136 --> 08:34.305
then you're looking
at four, maybe five years.

08:34.388 --> 08:36.390
-And compiling, analyzing the data.
-Right.

08:38.893 --> 08:39.894
[laughs] Well...

08:42.063 --> 08:43.064
It's a shame.

08:44.815 --> 08:47.693
We have an interview with Miller
in an hour and it's a bit of a drive.

08:50.863 --> 08:52.657
You know, this is really important work.

08:52.740 --> 08:54.367
If your boss won't let you do it,

08:54.450 --> 08:57.370
then you should talk to someone
who has the freedom and resources to--

08:57.453 --> 08:59.121
[Tench] We'll stick with it for now.

08:59.205 --> 09:01.707
It'll be slow going,
but we're not ready to give up yet.

09:01.791 --> 09:02.959
Of course not.

09:03.042 --> 09:06.337
But it's good to get some encouragement,
even if our hands are tied.

09:07.004 --> 09:07.838
Thank you.

09:08.673 --> 09:09.632
It's a pleasure.

09:11.717 --> 09:12.635
-What if--
-Don't.

09:12.718 --> 09:14.136
-I'm just saying we could--
-Holden.

09:16.889 --> 09:18.641
Look, I'm frustrated too.

09:21.352 --> 09:25.648
You know, they shoot the birds in the yard
because they might be smuggling in drugs.

09:27.858 --> 09:30.987
Actually, I don't know if that's true.
A girlfriend told me once.

09:31.487 --> 09:33.573
-You date a lot of ex-cons?
-No.

09:34.991 --> 09:38.828
Actually, Debbie's the first girl
I've really dated-dated since high school.

09:38.911 --> 09:40.580
-Dated-dated.
-Yeah.

09:41.163 --> 09:43.833
My wife's the first woman
that I've married-married.

09:46.335 --> 09:48.671
I thought they said 3:00.
What are we waiting for?

09:48.754 --> 09:50.798
You'd be less fidgety
if you smoked cigarettes.

09:50.881 --> 09:52.049
[sighs]

09:52.133 --> 09:53.718
I should have brought a tape recorder.

09:54.218 --> 09:55.553
[door closes]

09:56.554 --> 09:58.431
[man] Bureau Agents Tench and Ford?

10:15.197 --> 10:18.326
Gentlemen. I'm Dr. Cale.
We spoke earlier on the phone.

10:18.409 --> 10:21.746
Thanks for doing this, Doctor.
We realize it's somewhat unorthodox.

10:21.829 --> 10:24.040
Unfortunately,
Miller says he won't talk to you.

10:24.123 --> 10:28.252
Now, we told him in advance and he agreed,
but there's really nothing we can do now.

10:28.336 --> 10:30.963
-He should be in a better mood tomorrow.
-Tomorrow?

10:31.047 --> 10:32.632
Well, he gets like this sometimes.

10:32.715 --> 10:35.343
Just needs a cool-off period
before he can interact with people.

10:35.426 --> 10:38.262
We have to bring him food into his cell
because he won't come out.

10:38.346 --> 10:40.431
We're headed out tonight.
We can't come in tomorrow.

10:40.514 --> 10:43.434
I'm sorry.
Will you be back to Boston another time?

10:44.435 --> 10:45.519
Perhaps.

10:45.603 --> 10:47.563
Thanks for your time, Doctor.
We appreciate it.

10:47.647 --> 10:48.648
Of course.

10:51.817 --> 10:54.528
Well, that's the last time
we give them advanced notice.

11:05.456 --> 11:08.167
[steam hissing]

11:15.466 --> 11:16.509
Holden?

11:17.551 --> 11:19.387
Ever feel like you're on the cusp
of something,

11:19.470 --> 11:21.389
and it keeps spinning out
in your head?

11:22.431 --> 11:24.809
-Where'd you get that ironing board?
-Your closet.

11:24.892 --> 11:27.228
I just can't stop thinking
about this project.

11:27.311 --> 11:29.438
Dr. Carr said it could have
far-reaching consequences.

11:29.522 --> 11:32.024
Why are you up? Did you smoke my pot?

11:32.108 --> 11:35.528
I can't stop thinking about this project.
The idea is so exciting.

11:38.948 --> 11:39.949
Okay.

11:41.325 --> 11:43.828
Just don't wake me up
when you come back to bed.

11:44.578 --> 11:46.038
Rissell's an hour or so away,

11:46.122 --> 11:48.207
so we don't have to do Road School
to get to him.

11:49.041 --> 11:51.877
There's, uh... Vaughn Greenwood.

11:51.961 --> 11:54.588
-The Skid Row Slasher?
-Yeah, he's in California.

11:54.672 --> 11:56.132
Along with Herbert Mullin.

11:56.799 --> 11:58.384
The Cincinnati Strangler...

11:58.467 --> 12:00.344
-What's his name?
-Posteal Laskey Jr.

12:00.428 --> 12:02.847
-I assume he's in Cincinnati?
-Uh...

12:03.347 --> 12:04.181
Yeah.

12:04.265 --> 12:07.601
I like teaching the Midwest cops.
Hospitable guys.

12:07.685 --> 12:09.270
There's always Richard Speck in Illinois.

12:09.353 --> 12:12.440
-Great, we can do a Midwest sweep.
-Gerard John Schaefer.

12:12.523 --> 12:15.568
He killed at least 30, they think.
That was in Florida, though.

12:15.651 --> 12:17.486
I can't say no to a Florida golf course.

12:17.570 --> 12:20.156
[phone ringing]

12:26.954 --> 12:27.913
Bill Tench.

12:27.997 --> 12:30.749
- Hey, Bill. It's Roy Carver.
-Hey, Roy. What can I do for you?

12:30.833 --> 12:33.002
We need to talk.
There's been another attack.

12:33.085 --> 12:34.670
This time resulting in a fatality.

12:36.881 --> 12:39.008
-Got it.
-Can I get you guys back out here?

12:39.091 --> 12:40.843
Okay. Let me get back to you.

12:42.845 --> 12:44.847
-What's up?
-Carver.

12:44.930 --> 12:45.848
Been another one.

12:45.931 --> 12:48.767
Same age as Rosemary Gonzales,
only this time she's dead.

12:50.436 --> 12:53.189
Bill, my God! We're vindicated.

12:53.272 --> 12:55.774
What's the matter with you?
An old lady was just murdered.

12:59.278 --> 13:00.988
We can talk to Kemper again.

13:07.203 --> 13:09.497
Did she have a dog?
Please tell me there's a dog.

13:09.580 --> 13:12.166
A bigger dog. Slit from ear to ear.

13:12.249 --> 13:14.126
[gasps] Amen.

13:15.794 --> 13:17.880
[Tench]  Not only is this
exactly what we predicted,

13:17.963 --> 13:20.049
but he's getting a taste for it,
there will be more.

13:20.132 --> 13:21.467
A sequence killer.

13:21.550 --> 13:22.801
A sequence killer?

13:22.885 --> 13:24.887
What we're calling it
when they kill three or more.

13:24.970 --> 13:28.390
Is this a new classification?
Need to get a steno to put it in writing.

13:28.474 --> 13:29.892
You bet. I'll talk to Marge.

13:30.434 --> 13:32.394
This is what you were talking about
with the Kemper thing?

13:32.478 --> 13:35.481
We briefed them with a description.
We need to make sure they bring him in.

13:35.564 --> 13:38.359
-It's what we predicted.
-Thank you, Holden. I've been listening.

13:38.442 --> 13:41.779
-[Tench] We have to make this right.
-I agree. You do now.

13:43.155 --> 13:45.824
What are you waiting for?
You got a plane to catch.

13:46.325 --> 13:47.159
Yes, sir.

13:47.952 --> 13:50.663
[Dwight Twilley Band's
"Feeling in the Dark" playing]

13:59.296 --> 14:01.882
♪ Single sunray ♪

14:02.258 --> 14:04.718
♪ Going my way ♪

14:04.802 --> 14:07.888
♪ So you told me, you're the one ♪

14:07.972 --> 14:09.306
[Carver]  Name was Laura Conway.

14:09.390 --> 14:12.309
Living literally half a mile away,
practically up the street.

14:12.393 --> 14:15.437
Same thing exactly, same time of night
that Rosemary Gonzales was attacked,

14:15.521 --> 14:16.480
about 10:30 or 11:00.

14:16.564 --> 14:17.523
What about the dog?

14:17.606 --> 14:20.985
A dog like that must've put up a fight.
Your unsub will have bite marks.

14:21.777 --> 14:22.945
The dog's fucking lasagna.

14:23.028 --> 14:24.405
We rousted a bunch of kids,

14:24.488 --> 14:27.616
had an 18-year-old from the neighborhood
we liked, but he had an alibi.

14:27.700 --> 14:29.410
-What was it?
-He's a fry cook.

14:29.493 --> 14:32.037
Clocked in till midnight,
his coworkers vouch for him.

14:32.121 --> 14:33.581
You spoke to his boss?

14:33.664 --> 14:35.958
Yeah, one of these new burger joints.
Big corporate set up.

14:36.041 --> 14:37.251
Like McDonald's?

14:37.334 --> 14:39.670
-Actually, I don't remember.
-We might have to rethink.

14:39.753 --> 14:41.213
Look at that dog.

14:42.214 --> 14:45.718
Someone had a good fucking grip on it,
damn near eviscerated.

14:46.802 --> 14:49.555
Now this woman wasn't as frail
as Mrs. Gonzales.

14:49.638 --> 14:51.807
Whoever did this wasn't easily scared off.

14:53.851 --> 14:55.227
-Older.
-And determined.

14:55.311 --> 14:57.563
[Carver] I don't understand
the sexual assault part.

14:57.646 --> 15:00.399
-Why just groping? Why not rape her?
-Because he didn't want to.

15:00.482 --> 15:02.860
He just wanted to dominate
and humiliate her.

15:02.943 --> 15:06.113
-[exhales] That's one sick son of a bitch.
-Supposing he's 35, 40.

15:06.196 --> 15:08.365
Supposing these women
are his mom's age...

15:08.449 --> 15:10.993
-It's a mom thing.
-Wait, 40? Did I just hear you correctly?

15:11.076 --> 15:13.829
-This is not a kid.
-I've been rounding up teenagers.

15:13.913 --> 15:16.498
This time wasn't as frenzied.
It's not a teenager.

15:16.582 --> 15:19.960
[sighs] Sacramento DA reamed my ass
for hassling busboys,

15:20.044 --> 15:21.295
and you've changed your mind?

15:21.378 --> 15:24.173
It's not a one-off.
This isn't some random freak-out.

15:24.256 --> 15:26.508
-This guy is getting confident.
-At least late 20s.

15:26.592 --> 15:29.762
Physically mature. Emotionally immature.
Socially undeveloped.

15:29.845 --> 15:32.431
-Possibly still lives at home.
-Narcotics, maybe.

15:32.514 --> 15:35.142
That's why he beat her this badly,
didn't know when to stop.

15:35.225 --> 15:36.310
-You think?
-[Tench] Why not?

15:36.393 --> 15:38.687
Not if he lives at home.
Maybe he's married.

15:38.771 --> 15:40.773
-Or separated.
-Separated?

15:40.856 --> 15:42.900
Guys in unhappy marriages
have hair triggers.

15:42.983 --> 15:45.277
They lash out.
Especially when it comes to women.

15:45.361 --> 15:48.322
-I wouldn't know anything about that.
-Lucky you.

15:48.405 --> 15:50.950
You guys still think he's white?
Not Latino? Black?

15:51.033 --> 15:52.242
[sighs]

15:52.326 --> 15:56.413
I think blacks, Latinos might be
too respectful of an elderly woman.

15:56.497 --> 16:00.125
-My bet is poor white trash.
-Listen, we did talk to some older guys.

16:00.209 --> 16:02.461
And this one right here
is pretty interesting.

16:04.171 --> 16:05.881
Just came walking up off the street.

16:05.965 --> 16:08.384
"Hey, what happened? Did anybody see?"
He'd been drinking.

16:08.467 --> 16:10.803
One of these guys who likes
talking to cops, you know.

16:14.848 --> 16:15.933
We should talk to him.

16:17.476 --> 16:18.435
Sure.

16:34.868 --> 16:36.745
-Mom.
-[car doors slam]

16:39.081 --> 16:40.082
Good morning.

16:41.083 --> 16:42.501
Do you remember me?

16:42.584 --> 16:44.086
Yeah, I remember you.

16:45.879 --> 16:46.714
Mom!

16:51.343 --> 16:52.803
Ma'am, I'm Detective Roy Carver.

16:52.886 --> 16:54.972
These are my colleagues,
Bill Tench and Holden Ford.

16:55.055 --> 16:56.557
-Hello.
-[woman] What do you want?

16:56.640 --> 16:57.766
It's Dwight, right?

16:57.850 --> 17:00.686
-What do you want with him?
-These gentlemen are with the FBI.

17:01.687 --> 17:03.689
[woman] Well, now what has he done?

17:03.772 --> 17:06.775
Who the hell have you
brought into my home?

17:07.901 --> 17:08.986
[Carver] May we come in?

17:18.037 --> 17:20.080
FBI knocking at my door.

17:22.332 --> 17:24.877
I might as well be dead for all he cares.

17:24.960 --> 17:27.671
Just kill me now
because that is what you're doing.

17:27.755 --> 17:29.506
And it is a slow death.

17:30.007 --> 17:33.302
He's my only son.
I might as well walk up to the freeway,

17:33.385 --> 17:37.431
stick my head under a truck
and save myself the misery.

17:39.224 --> 17:41.518
We'd just like to ask Dwight
a few questions.

17:41.602 --> 17:42.936
Are these yours, Dwight?

17:43.020 --> 17:47.566
You'd think he'd be out of my hair by now.
Move the fuck on, but no.

17:48.400 --> 17:51.445
-You sleep on the couch?
-When he's not too drunk to get up there.

17:53.113 --> 17:55.991
Maybe we can talk outside, Dwight.
Have a smoke.

17:56.075 --> 17:57.159
Take him.

17:57.743 --> 18:00.871
Just give me a fucking moment to breathe.

